[2] European Union
Date: Wed 6 Dec 2017
Source: Euronews [edited]
http://www.euronews.com/2017/12/06/measles-deaths-in-eu-on-course-to-treble


Measles deaths and infections are on course to treble in the European Union, latest figures have revealed. Cases have jumped from 3805 last year to more than 10 000 in the first 9 months of 2017, driven by spikes in Romania and Italy, data from the World Health Organization (WHO) has shown. There were 30 deaths from January to September [2017], against 12 last year [2016], according to European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control.

Romania, which has suffered more than 2-thirds of the EU's measles deaths this year [2017], has a lower-than-average immunisation rate. The percentage of 1-year-olds who have had the measles vaccine stood at 86 percent last year, compared with 85 percent in Italy. WHO says countries should have immunisation rates of 95 percent to protect the wider population. It warns immunisation rates in Europe have fallen from 95 percent to 93 percent over the last 5 years.

Romania and Italy have both moved to make immunisations mandatory this year. 'Pseudoscience' and media gossip in Romania have worked to induce high levels of skepticism towards vaccines, according to www.vaccinestoday.eu

Dr Valeria Herdea, president of a professional medical organisation in Romania, told the website: "We still have gossip shows in the media, with different celebrities of dubious taste, who provide all kind of 'magic methods' for child immunity, without vaccination, but who capture public attention much more than scientific information. This is increasing the percentage of those who became suddenly anti-vaccination or at least hesitant."

The latest figures come as health chiefs in England warned unvaccinated people planning on traveling to Italy and Romania.

Last year [2016] a director of an immunisation programme in South America, which has been declared free of measles, told Euronews he was concerned immigration from Europe would threaten the continent's achievement.

Europe is a world leader when it comes to skepticism over vaccines, according to a survey by the Vaccine Confidence Project.

[Byline: Chris Harris]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[See figures and table in the report URL: Fig 1, How measles cases in the EU have nearly trebled in recent years; Fig 2, How measles deaths breakdown over the last 2 years; Table 1, Measles cases in the EU (2015-2017)

As exemption rates rise, "herd immunity" is weakened. This is the idea that immunity by vaccination or previous illness of a large percentage of a population helps protect those who are not vaccinated, such as those with medical conditions that prevent them from receiving immunizations. Herd immunity limits the disease's opportunity to spread and helps prevent against outbreaks, according to the CDC - which could be threatened if numbers of exemptions continue to rise. - Mod.LK]

******
[3] Greece
Date: Sat 9 Dec 2017
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/greece-reports-measles-outbreak-south-hardest-hit-65285/


While Europe has been seeing a measles outbreak during the past 2 years or so, affecting thousands, Greece has been largely unaffected until recent months. Since August 2017, 364 measles cases have been reported with 167 reported in October [2017] alone.

The Hellenic Centre for Disease Control and Prevention (KEELPNO) says the majority of the cases have been reported from South Greece, affecting mainly people of Greek nationality (mainly young Roma children, as well as Greek adults mainly aged 25-44 years old) susceptible to measles, among them healthcare professionals who were unvaccinated or partly vaccinated. One death has been reported in a laboratory confirmed measles case, concerning a Roma infant 11 months old, with underlying dystrophy, unvaccinated, who died of septicemia.

KEELPNO expects more cases and says the spread to other geographic areas cannot be excluded.

Vaccination with the combined measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccine is recommended for children, adolescents and adults who have not been vaccinated with the appropriate doses. According to the National Immunization Program, children, adolescents and adults who were born after 1970 and have no evidence of immunity should receive 2 doses of measles containing vaccine.

[Byline: Robert Herriman]

