[5] United Kingdom (Surrey)
Date: Mon 11 Dec 2017, 11:32 PM
Source: getSurrey [edited]
http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/surrey-news/measles-surrey-warning-issued-following-14021581


A total of 7 cases of measles, an "extremely infectious" disease, have been confirmed in Surrey. Public Health England (PHE) is urging people across the county to check that they are up to date with the MMR vaccine following the diagnoses in North West Surrey.

PHE has warned it is possible for people of any age to contract the illness and that it can lead to serious complications. It is extremely infectious and so anyone with symptoms has been advised to stay at home and phone their GP ... to prevent it spreading.

Dr Margot Nicholls, consultant in communicable disease control with PHE south east, said: "Measles is extremely infectious. Christmas is fast approaching and gatherings will be held where the disease can spread easily. It is really important that anyone who hasn't had 2 doses of the MMR vaccine contacts their GP surgery to get up-to-date. If you're unsure whether you or your children have had the vaccine, check your child's Red Book or contact your GP surgery to find out. You do not need to seek additional vaccines if you and your children have had 2 MMR vaccines in the past."

Dr Nicholls added: "With ongoing outbreaks in other parts of Europe including Romania, Italy and Germany, we're also warning that anyone travelling to these countries for the festive period is at particular high risk. If you're planning to go to these countries, contact your GP to arrange an appointment for vaccination before you travel, if you've not received 2 MMR doses in the past. The MMR vaccine is free and parents are offered the 2 jabs for their children when the little ones turn 1 and again at 3 years, 4 months. If you have missed either of your jabs, PHE has said it is important that you get up to date with your GP, particularly in light of the recent cases."

Children should have their 1st MMR jab at 1 and a booster at 3 years and 4 months with lots of other people "so stay away from any Christmas gatherings if you have symptoms, and especially from vulnerable patients in hospitals, care homes or other settings. We understand Christmas is a time to visit loved ones, but measles can be serious for these groups and spreads easily in these places."

[Byline: Zosia Eyres]

