******
[6] United Kingdom
Date: Mon 11 Dec 2017
Source: Daily Star [edited]
https://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/666235/Measles-outbreak-epidemic-virus-NHS-vaccine-Manchester-Leeds-Liverpool-Birmingham-UK


A measles outbreak has strengthened its grip on the country after initially flaring up in Liverpool and Leeds. Now it's spread to Manchester and Birmingham, with the strain initially thought to have originated in Europe.

As many as 4 children in Manchester have been confirmed to have the highly-contagious bug which causes a blotchy red rash. In Birmingham, 9 cases of the virus, which also causes cold-like symptoms, a fever, aches and pains, have also been confirmed. It comes after 28 confirmed cases in Leeds and 18 in Liverpool. Cases have also been reported in Surrey and Sussex.

Brits are now being urged to have their children vaccinated, something controversial columnist Katie Hopkins is a staunch opponent of.

Dr Will Welfare, Consultant in Health Protection with Public Health England, told the Manchester Evening News: "Measles is a very infectious virus and can spread rapidly among communities, such as schools, if people have not been fully immunised. I would appeal to any parents who have not yet had their children vaccinated to get them protected as soon as possible through their GP."

The NHS say measles can be prevented by having the vaccination, offered by the health service as a single measles, mumps and rubella jab.

[Byline: Nicholas Bieber]

